{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"52bbf202-e643-4e0f-ab3d-253922626bbb","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle methods**. You subclass `Window` and override the corresponding methods:\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (`Window`) |\n|---------------|----------------------|\n| `OnStart` | `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep` | `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume` | `OnResumed()` |\n\n**Example:**\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated() { /* OnStart equivalent */ }\n    protected override void OnStopped() { /* OnSleep equivalent */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed() { /* OnResume equivalent */ }\n}\n```\n\nThen in your `App` class, override `CreateWindow`:\n\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        return new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAdditional `Window` overrides available: `OnActivated()`, `OnDeactivated()`, and `OnDestroying()` for more granular control.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f1a6d55e-2d75-4e17-b577-4c1d50658f8c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a straightforward knowledge question about the MAUI lifecycle API.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` class. In .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You now use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleEventHandler` approach.\n\nSpecifically, in .NET MAUI:\n- You can override `CreateWindow` in your `Application` class and subscribe to window lifecycle events\n- Or you can use the platform-specific lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`\n\n\n- You can also create a custom `Window` class and override its lifecycle methods directly\n\nThe mapping is fairly straightforward: `OnStart` maps to `Window.Created`, `OnSleep` corresponds to `Window.Deactivated` or `Window.Stopped`, and `OnResume` maps to `Window.Activated` or `Window.Resumed`. The key difference is that the `Application` class no longer has these lifecycle methods—they've been moved to the `Window` level in MAUI. available as overrides in the same way.\n\nWait, let me reconsider - .NET MAUI's `Application` class actually doesn't expose `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` like Xamarin.Forms did. Instead, the lifecycle methods moved to the `Window` class. I can override `CreateWindow()` in my `App` class and work with a custom `Window` subclass that has methods like `OnCreated()`, `OnActivated()`, `OnDeactivated()`, `OnStopped()`, `OnResumed()`, and `OnDestroying()` to handle the app lifecycle. The pattern is to create a custom window class with these overrides and return it from `CreateWindow()`.","outputTokens":868,"requestId":"081E:1F45CF:A8750E:C2667B:69F2A8AE"},"id":"f12da552-9b60-4d65-9632-c3de3cda4f43","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:56:31.649Z","parentId":"12359871-875b-4f11-b366-5b4976ad2cc9"}
